    summary:
      "This passage contains what may be the most pastorally devastating line in the New Testament: 'We do not have a high priest who is unable to sympathize with our weaknesses, but we have one who has been tempted in every way, just as we are — yet he did not sin.' The author isn't making an abstract theological point. This is pastoral care at the highest level. The community is suffering, and the author's response is not a lecture on endurance but a portrait of a God who knows exactly what suffering feels like from the inside.\n\nThe high priest imagery would have been immediately legible to a Jewish audience. The high priest entered the Holy of Holies once a year on the Day of Atonement, carrying blood to make purification for the people's sins. He was chosen from among the people specifically so he could 'deal gently with the ignorant and wayward, since he himself is subject to weakness.' The author takes this job description and applies it to Jesus — but with a critical upgrade. Every human high priest offered sacrifices for his own sins first. Jesus didn't need to. His sympathy with human weakness is not theoretical; it's experiential. He was tempted. He wept. He suffered. But he didn't sin.\n\nThe passage climaxes with a raw, almost uncomfortable description of Jesus in Gethsemane: 'During the days of Jesus' life on earth, he offered up prayers and petitions with fervent cries and tears to the one who could save him from death.' This is not the serene, haloed Jesus of Renaissance painting. This is a man screaming.",
