    verseEnd: 28,
    summary:
      "Melchizedek appears in Genesis for exactly three verses. He's the king of Salem, a priest of God Most High, and he blesses Abraham after a military victory. Abraham gives him a tenth of the spoils. Then Melchizedek vanishes from the narrative as suddenly as he arrived. He has no genealogy, no birth narrative, no death notice. In the Hebrew Scriptures, that silence is just a feature of compressed storytelling. The author of Hebrews turns it into a theological argument.\n\nThe reasoning is intricate and brilliant. Because Melchizedek has no recorded beginning or end, the author says he 'remains a priest forever' — a type of the eternal priesthood of Christ. Because Abraham tithed to Melchizedek, and because Levi was still 'in Abraham's body' when Abraham paid that tithe, Levi himself symbolically submitted to Melchizedek's priesthood. Therefore the Melchizedek priesthood is superior to the Levitical one. It's the kind of argument that would have made a first-century rabbi's eyes light up.\n\nThe payoff is enormous: if the Levitical priesthood could have made people perfect, there would have been no need for a different priest to arise. But a different priest did arise — one from the tribe of Judah, which has nothing to do with the altar. Jesus doesn't become a priest by genealogy; he becomes a priest by the power of an indestructible life.",
