    modernParallel:
      "Melchizedek is the Bible's great reminder that God has always been working outside the lines we draw. Three verses in Genesis 14. No tribe, no pedigree, no institutional backing. And yet this mysterious figure becomes the template for the most important priesthood in human history. For anyone who has ever felt that they don't have the right credentials, the right background, the right connections — Melchizedek is your patron saint. Legitimacy in God's economy doesn't come from genealogy. It comes from calling.\n\nThe institutional implications are enormous too. Every religious system eventually calcifies around its own procedures. The Levitical priesthood was God's idea, and even it was temporary. The author of Hebrews is saying: don't confuse the scaffolding with the building. The scaffolding served its purpose, but the building is Christ. When denominations fight over polity, when churches split over worship styles, when Christians insist that their particular form of church government is the biblical model — Hebrews 7 quietly suggests that every model is provisional. The only permanent priest is the one with an indestructible life.\n\nAnd that phrase — 'the power of an indestructible life' — is one to sit with. Not the power of a compelling personality, a strategic plan, a large budget, or a viral social media presence. The power of a life that death itself could not end. That's the foundation of the Christian hope, and it doesn't depend on anything we build.",
